<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-04-07T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-04-07T16:00:00-05:00" n="199" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d199">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">853B.20/48: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Portugal</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Fish</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lisbon</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-04-07T22:00:00+01:00">April 7,
                                    1942—10 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received April 7—9:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>295. Department’s telegrams 319, March 31, 9 p.m. and 326, April 1, 2
                                [<hi rend="italic">10</hi>] p.m. I at once sent notes to the Foreign
                            Minister in the sense of those telegraphic instructions and requested an
                            appointment with Sampayo<note n="20" xml:id="d199fn20">Teixeira de
                                Sampayo, Portuguese Secretary General for Foreign Affairs.</note> in
                            order to take up matter orally. He had left for the country to be gone
                            over Good Friday and Easter. I have repeated my request but the Foreign
                            Office has not yet fixed an appointment.</p>
                        <p>The British inform me they have sent to the Foreign Office a note along
                            the lines of the Department’s telegram No. 319.</p>
                        <p>I shall not fail to telegraph further as soon as I have seen the
                            Secretary General.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Fish</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>